# Question

You are given a list of events where each event is a tuple with a start and a finish time (in the format 'YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM'). Write a function `event_scheduler` that checks for any scheduling conflicts among the events. The function should return "No conflicts" if there are no overlapping events and "Conflict" if any events overlap in time. If the list is empty, return "No events". Use package Dates for parsing.

# Solution

```julia
using Dates

function event_scheduler(events)
    if isempty(events)
        return "No events"
    end
    
    for i in 1:length(events)-1
        event1 = events[i]
        for j in i+1:length(events)
            event2 = events[j]
            start_time1, end_time1 = Dates.parse.("YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM", [Dates.format(event1[1], "yyyy-mm-dd HH:MM"), Dates.format(event1[2], "yyyy-mm-dd HH:MM")])
            start_time2, end_time2 = Dates.parse.("YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM", [Dates.format(event2[1], "yyyy-mm-dd HH:MM"), Dates.format(event2[2], "yyyy-mm-dd HH:MM")])
            if (start_time2 < end_time1 && start_time1 < end_time2) || (end_time2 > start_time1 && end_time1 > start_time2)
                return "Conflict"
            end
        end
    end
    
    return "No conflicts"
end
```

This function `event_scheduler` takes a list of events as input. It first checks if the list is empty and returns "No events" in that case. If there are events, it loops through all possible pairs of events to check for scheduling conflicts. If any pair of events overlap in time, it will return "Conflict". Otherwise, it will return "No conflicts".
